column9: Meta

orig=Thursday, 7th: At 7 this morning it was snowing fast with wind due East, temp. 17.5 degrees. Should say that there were 9 inches of snow on ground, fallen since last night. 9 AM, wind commenced moving round to North gradually until at 1 PM it was north-west, temp. being 29 degrees below zero. The mercury gradually sinking till 3 PM it was 6.7 below, wind blowing a gale from north-west. 9 PM temp. was 13.4 below, wind a gale from north-west. The day and night was the most terrific (for a combination of wind, cold and drifting snow) witnessed in this section of Canada for years. Certainly never seen by the observer since 1853, the time of this coming to Niagara. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: Niagara_UCGS-200_M1958_1861-02-01_OBS-D.jpg

orig=Prevailing clouds this month were the cumulus (class). I have not known the month of March since 1853 to have been so cold as was that of 1861. orig=Towards early morning of 3rd, wind was South, rain having stopped about midnight.
